This staging table stores the account deviation details like underwriting, policy exception, etc. Policy exceptions occur when a required procedure does not take place. However, if there are any shortcomings, small enough not to be rejected but still not in order, such situations are called Deviations.  On the other hand, an underwriting exception is a deviation from the established credit requirements for a borrower. When the credit score of the borrower, debt-to-income ratio, or loan-to-value ratio, etc. do not meet the defined standards of the financial institution, an underwriting exception occurs. Underwriting exceptions are important from a fair lending perspective and are typically evaluated during the compliance review.

This staging table stores the lendable percent at an account level granularity. Lendable percent is a factor used to determine the amount of secured funding that a bank can expect to receive by multiplying it with the fair value of the asset that can be potentially provided as collateral. Lendable value is required for generating FR2052 a report. This table captures the lendable percent at an account level for all those assets, such as loans, which do not have a CUSIP code.

This staging table relates an account to a peer group. It is used to compare account activity to more than one peer group. One account can be part of many peer groups. The peer grouping can be based on any number of criteria. Groupings can be created at the customer account level or focused at the correspondent bank level. There is complete flexibility in the manner in which the relationship is defined. Grouping can be by industry or by customer size or by risk etc. This activity is done for the purpose of monitoring transaction whether activity is normal compared to a customer’s account peer group. Behaviour is detected when a customer’s transaction activity deviates substantially from its peer group of accounts or from its peer group of correspondent banks.

Portfolios are user defined group of accounts. This dimension table holds the master list of all the portfolios of the Institution. For example, auto loan portfolio is a group of auto loans.

This staging table contains the holdings of specific securities in customer accounts on a given day. The holding is measured by a financial instrument in terms of share or contract quantity, current security price and type of position. The file should contain only active customer accounts. Each position in this table will be linked with the trading account number, specific instrument code and position type. Aggregation of positions can be derived from other product processors tables which are linked with trading account number.

This staging table defines position pairings that relate a primary position and its offsetting position. The position pairs can be in any manner held for example, cash or margin. It contains only active customer account positions. Position pairing data is used to identify the relationships between security positions that might reflect those trading strategies, particularly for option strategies for example, debit spreads, credit spreads, or covered calls. The short position in an option pairing strategy must be listed as the primary position and the long position listed as the offsetting position. For a position known to be uncovered, the offsetting information can be defaulted for example, v_offset_instrument_id = 0-0, n_offset_unit_qty = 0 or left null. For a position pair involving positions in the same account, the v_offset_account_number should be left null. For each position pair relationship, exactly one record should be provided. In other words, the relationship between Position A and Position B should be reflected as either {A,B} or {B,A} but not both.

This Dimension stores the details of all the Annuitization options. This option indicates whether or not the contract holder has elected to take the annuitization benefit. Annuitization provisions are standard base contract provisions that allow for contract holders to have an accumulated balance paid to them under a stream of payments. This is a very typical contract provision used with contracts whose fundamental purpose is to provide a savings vehicle (e.g., forms of deferred annuities).
Values is
ANNUITY is 100% Annuitization elected
LUMPSUM is Lump sum withdrawal elected or no annuity
PARTIAL is Some portion is withdrawn as lump sum and remain is annuitized.

This staging or product processor entity captures the details of annuity contracts which are defined as a written agreement between a financial institution and a customer outlining each partys obligations in an annuity coverage agreement. This document will include the specific details of the contract, such as the structure of the annuity variable or fixed, any rider attached to the contract, any free look period attached to the policy or not, grace period allowed or not etc. This entity stores the specific details of the contract, such as the structure of the annuity variable or fixed, any penalties for early withdrawal, spousal provisions such as a survivor clause and rate of spousal coverage, and more. This entity will cover all the annuity contract held by the financial institution of their customers. Annuity is used as post retirement tool, where the customer makes series of investment payment to the annuity up to a certain period to create a corpus; the annuity then makes a series of payments to the customer of the annuity, which can be either monthly, quarterly, semi annually or yearly. An immediate annuity is where the customer has a lump sum cash, which he would like to annuitize, however deferred annuity accumulates fund over a period of time before making annuity payments to the customer. The amount thus invested accumulates interest on a compound basis before making annuity payments. They charge commission for administrative expense and surrender charges should the customer abruptly close the annuity. Fixed rate annuities do not provide any options on the assets that the funds can be invested in, whereas the variable rate annuity provides the option to invest in different assets. Retirement contracts which covers accumulation as well as payment, contract should be stored in this entity. When policyholder holds retirement contracts only in accumulation period and purchases annuity contract separately on date of retirement, a new annuity contract is expected to be opened in Stage Annuity contract entity.

This staging master entity stores the annuity payout type. Sample values are FIX : Level Annuities, With fixed annuities, the payout is a pre-determined sum of money that doesn’t change from the contract agreement. The fixed annuity is the most predictable and stable of all the annuity types. It carries the lowest risk, and possibly a lower return for the investor. VAR: Variable Annuities, With variable annuities, the money is invested in a fund of professionally managed investments like stocks, bonds or money market funds. Investors who purchase variable annuities can choose from a selection of subaccounts, which are mutual funds. ESC : Escalating Annuities, With Escalating Annuities, they tend to offer a much lower starting income, but the pay out increases each year – either by a set percentage, or in line with inflation as defined by the Retail Prices Index. They may end up paying more than a level annuity if you live for a long time.

This product processor entity captures the details of borrowing contract. Borrowing refers to receiving something of value in exchange for an obligation to pay back something of usually greater value at a particular time in the future. Borrowing contract will cover the loans which financial institution has borrowed from other financial institution and bonds which are issued by the financial institution. This entity captures Federal or Central bank Funds, Fixed Rate and floating rate Bonds, Zero Coupon Bonds and STRIPS.
Excess reserves that commercial banks deposit at regional Federal Reserve banks. Federal funds can then be lent to other commercial banks with insufficient reserves. These loans are made at a relatively low interest rate, called the federal funds rate or overnight rate, and they typically have an extremely short duration: overnight. Federal funds help commercial banks meet their daily reserve requirements. Banks are required to maintain a certain level of reserves based on the amount of customer deposits they are responsible for.
Fixed rate bond is a bond that pays the same amount of interest for its entire term. The benefit of owning a fixed-rate bond is that investors know with certainty how much interest they will earn and for how long. As long as the bond issuer does not default, the bondholder can predict exactly what his return on investment will be.
Floating rate note is a debt instrument with a variable interest rate. Also known as a floater or FRN, an interest rate of the floating rate note is tied to a benchmark such as the U.S. Treasury bill rate, LIBOR, the fed funds or the prime rate. Floaters are mainly issued by financial institutions and governments, and they typically have a two- to five-year term to maturity.
Zero coupon bond is a debt security that does not pay interest (a coupon) but is traded at a deep discount, rendering profit at maturity when the bond is redeemed for its full face value.
STRIPS is defined as the process of removing coupons from a bond and then selling the separate parts as a zero coupon bond and interest paying coupons. Also known as a stripped bond or zero coupon bond.

Users received rewards or bonus points and cash back as benefits of using credit cards. This staging entity will holds the transaction details of the credit cards which are issued to the customer by financial institutions. An individual can use credit card for domestic as well as international transactions. There are various transactions that individual can perform on a card like cash withdrawal on an ATM from credit card, purchase of merchandise, EMI transactions, loans against cards, utility payments, bill payments, credit shield, balance transfer, fees payment, interest payment etc. This table will also record the transaction details of card holder paying his monthly card bill to the issuer. Customer can use various method of paying the bill as cash, cheque etc. This will also records the details of method like if customer use cheque to pay his bill, this table will record the details like when it gets cleared or if the cheque is bounced etc. Each transaction will be tracked with the card account number.
Customer can originate loans against card as well, in this case this transaction table will have loan conversion field as yes and the respective transaction will have suppression flag as yes and corresponding contract will get generated in loan contract table with the link from offset account identifier.
Customer can pay his utility bills through card like electricity bills, phone bills etc. Customer can also avail the facility of credit shield where this protection gives customer the option to have the outstanding balance on his Credit Card waived in case of some unforeseen circumstances of loss of life due to any cause and permanent disability. This feature can also be used against loss of employment.
This entity will also hold the minute details of transactions like if the transaction is automated or if the transaction was routed by the customer service or if the transaction has crossed the limit etc.
The authorization process of cards involves when a customer uses the card at merchant place and Merchant accepts card and sends transaction details to card association like Visa or card etc. Association forwards transaction to the credit card acquirer institution and issuer institution for authorization through the Association (Visa, MasterCard). Issuers approve or reject transaction and sends notification back through same channels. Various channels involved in the transaction process are internet, phone etc. This table will hold all the transaction related data of credit cards and contract data of credit cards is available in stage cards table.

This product processor entity stores Current Account and Savings Account data of the financial institution. Demand Deposit comprises of Current and Savings Account, held at a bank or other financial institutions with no maturity. The funds deposited are payable on demand and hence pay low interest rate compared to a term deposit or sometimes no interest rate for Current Account holders. Savings account can be open in local currency, foreign currency and multi currency. Banks encourage cashless transactions by way of cheque, Demand Draft, Electronic Clearance System etc. However, cash withdrawal is possible through Automated Teller Machine (ATMs) up to a maximum cap as prescribed by the bank. Current Account is offered to Corporate, Small and Medium Enterprises (SME), Partnership firms and sole proprietors while Savings account is largely offered to all the retail individual account holders.

Account can be owned by multiple individuals, jointly with corporate, government or trust or NGO and   can be transacted through multiple channels like branch, internet, telephone. Financial institutions allow transactions into and out of the account through financial instruments like cheque, bankers cheque, or through electronic   payment systems like ACH (Automated Clearing House), RTGS (Real Time Gross   Settlement). Nomination and guardian facility for minor account is also provided with this product.

Financial institutions also provides value added benefits like utility payments, door-step banking etc.

CASA products are very important to banks for numerous reasons as the cost of deposit, which is calculated based on the interest rate paid by the banks divided by the deposit amount, has a direct impact on banks profitability. With cheaper funds, banks can lend at a profit. The banks do not pay any interest on current accounts and pay interest at a comparatively lesser rates on savings accounts. This results in increased net interest income (NII) or net income margin (NIM).

FDIC insurance covers all deposit accounts at insured banks and savings associations, including checking, NOW (Negotiable Order of Withdrawal) accounts, savings accounts, money market deposit accounts, and certificates of deposit (CDs) up to the insurance limit.

A foreign exchange contract is defined as a Commitment to buy or sell a specified amount of foreign currency on a fixed date and rate of exchange. Such contracts are used usually by importers as a hedge against exchange rate fluctuations. A foreign exchange contract is an agreement between an individual or entity and financial institution to exchange one currency for another at an agreed exchange rate on an agreed settlement date. On the settlement date, there is physical delivery of one currency in exchange for the other currency and the amount you pay in the currency you deliver is determined by the agreed exchange rate. A commodity is a necessary good that is used in trade for exchange of other commodities. Spot commodities traded on the spot market with an expectation of immediate sale and delivery at settlement.

This entity captures the details of forward contracts. Forward contract is defined as a customized contract between two parties to buy or sell an asset at a specified price on a future date. A forward contract can be used for hedging or speculation, although its non-standardized nature makes it particularly apt for hedging. Unlike standard futures contracts, a forward contract can be customized to any commodity, amount and delivery date. A forward contract settlement can occur on a cash or delivery basis. Forward contracts do not trade on a centralized exchange and are therefore regarded as over-the-counter (OTC) instruments. While their OTC nature makes it easier to customize terms, the lack of a centralized clearinghouse also gives rise to a higher degree of default risk. As a result, forward contracts are not as easily available to the retail investor as futures contracts. This entity will cover all the forward contract held by the financial institution of their customers.

The important differences between futures and forwards:
Contract size is decided by the exchange in the case of futures while it is bilateral in the case of forwards.
Price of the contract is decided by the market in the case of futures while it is decided by the counterparty in the case of forward
Margin is required in a futures contract, while it is not mandatory in a forwards contract
Number of Contracts is standardized as decided by the exchange, while in a forward contract it is not standardized
Settlement is by way of cash in a futures contract whereas a forward contract is through delivery of the underlying to the counterparty.

This product processor entity captures the details of investment contract. Investment is defined as a monetary asset purchased with the idea that the asset will provide income in the future or appreciate and be sold at a higher price. This entity will cover bonds, MBS, equities etc. where the customer will invest their money with the idea to generate more income in future. This entity will cover products like Government and Municipal Bonds, Covered or Secured Bonds, Corporate Bonds, Fixed Rate and floating rate Bonds, Zero Coupon Bonds, STRIPS and Junk or high yield Bonds.
Municipal bond is defined as a debt security issued by a state, municipality or county to finance its capital expenditures. Municipal bonds are exempt from federal taxes and from most state and local taxes, especially if you live in the state in which the bond is issued.
Covered bond is defined as securities created from public sector loans or mortgage loans where the security is backed by a separate group of loans. Covered bonds typically carry a 2-10 year maturity rate and enjoy relatively high credit ratings, depending on the quality of the pool of loans (cover pool) backing the bond.
Secured bond is a type of bond that is secured by the issuers pledge of a specific asset, which is a form of collateral on the loan. In the event of a default, the bond issuer passes title of the asset or the money that has been set aside onto the bondholders. Secured bonds can also be secured with a revenue stream that comes from the project that the bond issue was used to finance.
Corporate bond is a debt security issued by a corporation and sold to investors. The backing for the bond is usually the payment ability of the company, which is typically money to be earned from future operations. In some cases, the companys physical assets may be used as collateral for bonds. Corporate bonds are considered higher risk than government bonds. As a result, interest rates are almost always higher, even for top-flight credit quality companies.
Fixed rate bond is a bond that pays the same amount of interest for its entire term. The benefit of owning a fixed-rate bond is that investors know with certainty how much interest they will earn and for how long. As long as the bond issuer does not default, the bondholder can predict exactly what his return on investment will be.
 Floating rate note is a debt instrument with a variable interest rate. Also known as a floater or FRN, a floating rate notes interest rate is tied to a benchmark such as the U.S. Treasury bill rate, LIBOR, the fed funds or the prime rate. Floaters are mainly issued by financial institutions and governments, and they typically have a two- to five-year term to maturity.
Zero coupon bond is a debt security that does not pay interest (a coupon) but is traded at a deep discount, rendering profit at maturity when the bond is redeemed for its full face value.
STRIPS is defined as the process of removing coupons from a bond and then selling the separate parts as a zero coupon bond and interest paying coupons. Also known as a stripped bond or zero coupon bond. 
Junk bond is a colloquial term for a high-yield or non-investment grade bond. Junk bonds are fixed-income instruments that carry a rating of BB or lower by Standard and Poors, or Ba or below by Moody. Junk bonds are so called because of their higher default risk in relation to investment-grade bonds.

This product processor entity captures the details of leases contracts. Leases contracts is defined as a formal document that identifies the lessor, lessee, and the leased asset or property; states lease term and fee (rent), and detailed terms and conditions of the lease agreement. A lease is a contractual arrangement calling for the lessee (user) to pay the lessor (owner) for use of an asset. This entity will cover capital lease and operating lease products.
A lease considered to have the economic characteristics of asset ownership. A capital lease would be considered a purchased asset for accounting purposes. An operating lease, on the other hand, would be handled as a true lease, or rental, for accounting purposes. The choice of lease classification will have important results on a firms financial statements. A lease falls into this category if any of the following requirements are met:
1. The life of the lease is 75 percent or greater of the assets useful life.
2. The lease contains a purchase agreement for less than market value.
3. The lessee gains ownership at the end of the lease period.
4. The present value of lease payments is greater than 90 percent of the assets market value.
A capital lease is an example of accrual accountings inclusion of economic events. Generally, companies have a choice of which type of lease they wish to use for accounting purposes, however, both types of leases provide specific advantages and disadvantages to financial statements. For example, companies wishing to show a higher return on asset ratios would choose an operating lease, as the balance sheet would not account for the item as an asset, thus reducing the denominator in the ratio.

This product processor entity captures the details of letter of credit contract. A letter of credit is a document from a bank guaranteeing that a seller will receive payment in full as long as certain delivery conditions have been met. In the event that the buyer is unable to make payment on the purchase, the bank will cover the outstanding amount. They are often used in international transactions to ensure that payment will be received where the buyer and seller may not know each other and are operating in different countries. In this case the seller is exposed to a number of risks such as credit risk, and legal risk caused by the distance, differing laws and difficulty in knowing each party personally. A letter of credit provides the seller with a guarantee that they will get paid as long as certain delivery conditions have been met. For this reason the use of letters of credit has become a very important aspect of international trade. This entity will cover products like Revocable Letter of Credit, Irrevocable Letter of Credit and Transferable Letter of Credit.
Revocable letter of credit that the granting bank or the letter holder (who is the buyer of some good) may cancel under some or any circumstances. This does not provide the seller with any extra assurance that he or she will be paid on time and in the correct amount. As a result they carry higher risk than irrevocable letters of credit.
An irrevocable letter of credit, or ILOC, cannot be canceled or modified in any way without explicit consent by the affected parties involved. For example, the issuing bank has no power to change the terms of an ILOC simply because the letter requester is having second thoughts. It should be noted, however, that ILOCs are in effect only for a specified time period and do, in fact, expire at a pre-determined point.
Transferable Letter of Credit is a letter of credit that permits the beneficiary of the letter to make some or all of the credit available to another party, thereby creating a secondary beneficiary. The party that initially accepts the transferable letter of credit from the bank is referred to as the first beneficiary. The bank issuing the letter of credit must approve the transfer.

This product processor entity captures the details of loan contracts. A loan contract is a contract between a borrower and a lender which regulates the mutual promises made by each party. There are many types of loan agreements, including facilities agreements, revolvers, term loans, working capital loans. Loan agreements are documented via a compilation of the various mutual promises made by the involved parties. This entity will covers all the different types of loans as personal loans, educational loans, auto loans, commercial loans, corporate loans, working capital loans, housing loans, syndicated loans.
Retail loans involves home equity loans, auto finance, consumer durable loans, educational loans, personal loans and cards loans.
In shared appreciation (SAM) The borrowers takes a loan against the property, usually 25 percent of the property value at the time of taking loan, No repayment is required to be made by the borrower. Borrower has a right to occupy the property till death or sale of the property. On sale of the property, the appreciation is shared between the borrower and the financial institution.
Auto loans has different categories as new auto loans, used auto loans, lease buyout etc. This loan is given against any vehicle.
Educational loans categorized as funded, partially secured. This loan is given against the education and normally the repayment starts after a certain time when the education finishes.
Personal loans categorized as funded, generally unsecured. Personal loans is given for any personal reasons.
Corporate loans are also given for setting up infrastructure or business. 
Amortized loans is a loan with scheduled periodic payments of both principal and interest. This is opposed to loans with interest-only payment features, balloon payment features and even negatively amortizing payment features.
Borrowers who choose amortized loans are less likely to experience payment shock than borrowers who choose loans which are not fully amortized. Payments on loans that are not initially fully amortized must at some point become amortized over the remaining term of the loan in order to repay the outstanding principal balance. The shorter the remaining term, the larger the increase required in the periodic payments to amortize the loan over the remaining term.
Loan life cycle involves Application, Appraisal of the parties, Sanctions, documentation, disbursement, repayment, servicing, status change, collection process, recall of loan, write off, debt sale and closure or rollover.
A syndicated loan is a loan extended to a single customer by multiple financial institutions, which are formed into a group, or syndicate, for that purpose. The same terms and conditions apply to all of the lenders in the syndication, and there is only one loan agreement. Measures represented in this table will represents the home bank exposure in the syndicate loan agreement.

• Correspondent - Mortgages acquired through the reporting institution's correspondent production channel. This includes all mortgage whole loans purchased on a recurring basis (flow) from another correspondent institution, eligible for securitization into the secondary markets or portfolio retention on the bank's balance sheet. Report as broker originated all third-party originated loans when the bank cannot distinguish between broker and correspondent originated.
• Bulk Purchase – Pools of mortgage whole loans purchased from a third party originator for the right to securitize or retention in the bank-owned portfolio. Residential Mortgages acquired for the Servicing Portfolio in this manner are typically negotiated as one-time transactions between a Mortgage Institution and an independent third party originator (Mortgage Company or Correspondent). Report all bulk acquisitions and correspondent flow acquisitions as correspondent originated when the institution cannot distinguish between these categories. Do not label bank acquisitions as Bulk Purchases.
• Servicing Rights Purchased - Refers to a separately negotiated purchase of mortgage servicing rights (PMSR) from a third party. When the servicer cannot distinguish between bulk whole loan and bulk servicing acquisitions, the servicer should report all of these acquisitions consistently in the category that represents the majority of the servicer's acquisitions. Note: This reporting category applies exclusively to the Servicing Portfolio.
• Wealth Management/Private Banking – report all loans originated through a servicer’s private wealth management or private banking division.

This product processor entity records call and put options that are bought(long) or sold(short) by the customer. Options contract provides a right but not an obligation to buy or sell the underlying to the holder of the options contract. The holder of the options is required to pay a premium to buy the options contract and the seller also known as the writer of the options contract receives the premium amount. The options contract specifies the underlying that is part of the contract, the strike date and strike price which is the price at which the holder of the call option can exercise to buy the underlying asset or holder of a put option can exercise to sell the underlying asset. If the option price at strike date is favorable to the holder (which the holder will exercise) then the option is considered in the money, if the  Options price at strike date is equal to strike price (no profit, no gain), then the option is considered as at the money and when the options is unfavorable to the holder (the underlying is available cheaper at the market) then the option is considered as out of the money. Financial institutions require a certain amount as Margin(cash collateral) from the customer, before allowing trading options. There are different style of options; European, American, Bermudan or Asian - European options can be exercised only on the strike date, while the American option can be exercised on any dayup to the strike date; the Bermudan option can be exercised multiple times at a predetermined strike date. An Asian option (also called an average option) is an option whose payoff is linked to the average value of the underlier on a specific set of dates during the life of the option.
Besides plain vanilla options, there are exotic options like Binary options(predicting the fluctuations in price), Barrier Options(option is active only at a specific price) , Quanto Options(settlement currency is different from the currency in which underlying is denominated) etc. Financial institutions combine all the variations available to make a strategy to enhance payoff. 
Some of the options strategies are Covered Call, Married Put, Bull Call Spread, Bear Put Spread, Long Straddle, Long Strangle, Butterfly Spread.

This product processor entity captures the details of overdraft contract. Overdraft is defined as an extension of credit from a lending institution when an account reaches zero. An overdraft allows the individual to continue withdrawing money even if the account has no funds in it. Basically the financial institution allows people to borrow a set amount of money. This entity will captures all the overdrafts occurred in CASA accounts.
n overdraft occurs when money is withdrawn from a bank account and the available balance goes below zero. In this situation the account is said to be overdrawn. If there is a prior agreement with the account provider for an overdraft, and the amount overdrawn is within the authorized overdraft limit, then interest is normally charged at the agreed rate. If the negative balance exceeds the agreed terms, then additional fees may be charged and higher interest rates may apply. Certain retail accounts could provide ATM overdraft where institutions or ATMs may allow cash withdrawals despite insufficient availability of funds. The account holder may or may not be aware of this fact at the time of the withdrawal. If the ATM is unable to communicate with the cardholders bank, it may automatically authorize a withdrawal based on limits preset by the authorizing network. The financial institution charges a fee unexpected to the account holder, creating a negative balance or leaving insufficient funds for a subsequent debit from the same account. The interest rates charged are tiered generally, which means that interest is charged on the entire amount in slabs much like the tax liability. Interest chargeable are capitalized to the account and use the limit allowed on the account.

This product processor entity captures prepaid card information. Prepaid card is a card issued by a financial institution that is preloaded with funds and is used like a normal credit card. A prepaid credit card works in the opposite way of a normal credit card, because instead of buying something with borrowed funds (through credit), you buy things with funds that have already been paid. This card functions like a gift card. A prepaid credit card allows a person the convenience of a credit card without going into debt. You can use them to purchase items online or in person, but since you must load them with funds before using them, you never spend more money than you have. These can be effective tools to teach kids about credit cards without allowing them to irresponsibly rack up charges that they ca not afford, or for those that have a hard time managing their finances and end up with tremendous amounts of credit card debt.

This entoty will hold the transaction details of prepaid card details which are issued by the financial institution. One must load the card with cash, and use it to withdraw cash or make purchases. Once your balance hits zero, person can not use the card to withdraw any more money or pay for any more goods. The transactions involved in prepaid card are the transaction loading the amount to this account and it will also hold the transaction details of using this card in any kind of purchasing.

against multiple homogenous credit identifiers. Each curve/series have a set of probability to default values
against multiple time periods.  Credit Identifiers could either be Rating or Delinquency Past Due days band.

based but not both. Ideally, a PD Term structure Identifier will be associated to a specific PD Term Structure
model which used by the banking institution to generate the PD values.

This product processor entity captures the details of repurchase contracts. This will be used to store the repurchase agreements wherein the bank acts as the principal or an agent. The principal transaction will be a bilateral transaction. The agent transaction will be a tri-party repo transaction, wherein the bank acting as agent on behalf of either the client or the dealer, will have the SFT transaction on its books. 
Repurchase agreement (REPO) is defined as a form of short-term borrowing for dealers in government securities. The dealer sells the government securities to investors, usually on an overnight basis, and buys them back the following day. For the party selling the security (and agreeing to repurchase it in the future) it is a repo; for the party on the other end of the transaction, (buying the security and agreeing to sell in the future) it is a reverse repurchase agreement. This entity covers both Repo and Reverse Repo instrument.

Repo is defined an agreement involving the sale of securities by one party to another with a promise to repurchase the securities at a specified price and on a specified future date. Repo has two legs. Both involve security settlement and funds settlement 

Reverse Repo is the purchase of securities with the agreement to sell them at a higher price at a specific future date. For the party selling the security (and agreeing to repurchase it in the future) it is a repo; for the party on the other end of the transaction (buying the security and agreeing to sell in the future) it is a reverse repurchase agreement.

This product processor entity captures  the details of swaps contract. A swap is a derivative in which two counterparties exchange cash flows of one partys financial instrument for those of the other partys financial instrument. The benefits in question depend on the type of financial instruments involved. For example, in the case of a swap involving two bonds, the benefits in question can be the periodic interest (coupon) payments associated with such bonds. Specifically, two counterparties agree to exchange one stream of cash flows against another stream. These streams are called the legs of the swap. The swap agreement defines the dates when the cash flows are to be paid and the way they are accrued and calculated.[1] Usually at the time when the contract is initiated, at least one of these series of cash flows is determined by an uncertain variable such as a floating interest rate, foreign exchange rate, equity price, or commodity price. This entity will cover all the swaps contracts held by the financial institution of their customers.

The plain vanilla swap is the interest rate swap where a counterparty exchanges fixed(or floating) interest rate in return for a floating(or fixed) rate (benchmark rate plus spread) on a notional principal primarily as a hedging strategy for a period of time. The other type of swaps are
currency swaps where the exchange of principal on the notional amounts is done at market rates, using the same rate for the transfer at inception as is employed at maturity, there are intermediate interest cash flows that are exchanged between parties. A cross Currency swap is useful to raise capital funding in a foreign market.

There are different types of swaps contract like accreting swaps, amortizing swaps, basis swap, cross currency swap.

This product processor entity captures the details of term deposit contract. Term deposit is defined as a deposit held at a financial institution that has a fixed term. These are generally short-term with maturities ranging anywhere from a month to a few years. When a term deposit is purchased, the lender (the customer) understands that the money can only be withdrawn after the term has ended or by giving a predetermined number of days notice. Term deposits are an extremely safe investment and are therefore very appealing to conservative, low-risk investors. By having the money tied up you will generally get a higher rate with a term deposit compared with a demand deposit. This entity covers products like regular fixed deposit, recurring deposit, tax saving deposit and certificate of deposits (CD) which are subscribed by financial institutions customers.
Account can be owned by multiple individuals, jointly with corporate, government or trust or NGO and   can be transacted through multiple channels like branch, internet, telephone. Financial institutions allow transactions into and out of the account through financial instruments like cheque, bankers cheque, or through electronic payment systems like ACH (Automated Clearing House), RTGS (Real Time Gross Settlement). Nomination and guardian facility for minor account is also provided with this product.
Fixed Deposit refers to a savings account or certificate of deposit that pays a fixed rate of interest until a given maturity date. Funds placed in a Fixed Deposit usually cannot be withdrawn prior to maturity or they can perhaps only be withdrawn with advanced notice and or by having a penalty assessed.
Recurring Deposit is a special kind of Term Deposit offered by banks  which help people with regular incomes to deposit a fixed amount every month into their Recurring Deposit account and earn interest at the rate applicable to Fixed Deposits.
Tax saving deposit is a special category of fixed deposits where the investor gets the benefit of a tax break when they invest a sum of money in the deposit. The maximum benefit is available up to an investment of Rs 1 lakh and there is a lock-in period of 5 years in the deposit.
Certificate of deposit (CD) is a savings certificate entitling the bearer to receive interest. A CD bears a maturity date, a specified fixed interest rate and can be issued in any denomination. CDs are generally issued by commercial banks and are insured by the FDIC. The term of a CD generally ranges from one month to five years.

body.logObjName: Trade Finance Contract Amendment Status Stage
body.desc:
This table identifies the status for a specific amendment event of a trade finance contract.  An amendment to
a contract is set to an “Unconfirmed” status by Oracle. The recipient of the amendment event may update the
status to “Confirm” or “Reject” on the changes made to the contract but is not necessarily required.  When the
recipient rejects a specific amendment event, all the changes made to a contract defined in that event is no
longer factored into the contract.

body.logObjName: Trade Finance Contract Event Acknowledgement Stage
body.desc:
This table identifies the acknowledgement of receipt of a specific event on a trade finance contract.  The
event that may typically be acknowledged is an issue or amendment event but is not required to be provided by
the recipient of the event such as the beneficiary receiving the letter of credit captured as an issue event
may not acknowledge receipt of this letter of credit.

This entity contains the risk and trust lists that are used to monitor transactional or trading activities for
money laundering or fraud. Watch Lists can be externally published lists such as those that the Office of
Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) and the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) publish, or they can be internal
lists that you develop for monitoring internal accounts or customers. Each list represents a single level of
risk or trust. Conceptually, a Watch List is a set of entities that all have the same level of risk.
The level of risk for a Watch List is reflected in its type. various types of watch list are Exempted, Trusted
and Risk. Entities on an Exempted Watch List are known not to be involved in money laundering activities and
should not be monitored for these behaviors. Entities on a Trusted Watch List are thought not to be involved
in money laundering but should be monitored less rigorously than the general population (that is, use higher
thresholds). Entities on a Risk Watch List are suspected of being involved in money laundering and should be
monitored more closely (that is, use lesser thresholds). Risk Watch Lists can vary in the degree of risk from
1 through 10 where the risk increases with the value. As the risk increases, an entities behavior is monitored
more closely.
